    <node id="1. Area of Education Policy Open to Consideration: Dr. Frank Atherton is open to considering the idea of setting a specific target or range for the number of staff members per student to support the health and education objectives of the plan, as he acknowledges that it is not his area of expertise and hasn't been discussed in the development of the strategy. He agrees to consider this point if it is specifically raised in the consultation response from the committee.&#10;2. Improving Implementation of Standards for Healthy Preschools: Dr. Frank Atherton suggests improving the implementation of standards for healthy preschools by potentially tightening the existing standards and enforcing them more strictly, ensuring compliance through proper implementation. He also mentions that there will be expectations on schools to provide not just healthy environments but to actively work towards well-being and healthy weight in children under the new curriculum. Dr. Atherton emphasizes the importance of local leadership to ensure accountability and the successful integration of 'Healthy Weight: Healthy Wales' with the new curriculum plans, which will place obligations on school leaders about what they do in their schools." />
