    <node id="1. The draft plan proposes encouraging local leadership in promoting healthy habits in schools, including physical activity in early primary education. This is a Tier 1 approach targeting the whole population.&#10;2. Consideration of statutory guidance for schools on physical education is also suggested, ensuring proper focus and resources, which remains within Tier 1.&#10;3. Engaging with children and young people to inform anti-obesity strategies through various forums such as school visits and consultations falls under Tier 1 community intervention.&#10;4. Developing targeted interventions to address the decline in physical activity among girls during teenage years can be seen as a Tier 2 intervention, targeting those at higher risk of obesity.&#10;5. Exploring opportunities for partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales to drive population-level approaches to physical activity also falls under Tier 1 community intervention.&#10;6. Improving the quality of food provided at schools, whether it is free or paid for, as well as addressing hunger at school through national-level initiatives can be considered both Tier 1 (universal) and Tier 2 (targeted) interventions depending on their implementation.&#10;7. Examining the potential benefits of having a second measurement taking place in the Child Measurement Programme to better understand the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children relates to identification and monitoring, which is crucial for appropriate weight management interventions (Tier 3).&#10;8. Although not explicitly mentioned, providing sufficient support for very overweight children would likely involve Tier 3 interventions such as referrals to specialized healthcare services, family-based lifestyle weight management programs, or in some cases, medical treatment. The draft plan does not provide specifics on this matter." />
    <node id="1. The importance of aligning existing governance systems in Wales, such as Public Services Boards and Regional Partnership Boards, is recognized as crucial for driving a common agenda for preventing obesity and other health issues. This alignment would help ensure that the 'Healthy Weight: Healthy Wales' strategy is not viewed in isolation but as part of a broader prevention strategy.&#10;2. There is an emphasis on maximizing the effectiveness of existing programs, evaluating their impact, and seeking better value from them before considering new investments. The potential for drawing upon existing resources and capacities across Wales is also highlighted to drive greater scale in addressing obesity-related services.&#10;3. It is acknowledged that setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student to support health and education objectives in schools is not explicitly mentioned in the transcript. However, there are discussions on encouraging local leadership, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;4. Addressing gaps in data on childhood obesity is considered essential, and implementing longitudinal measurements similar to England's approach (where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12) could provide valuable information on the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children. This information would help direct initiatives to reduce childhood obesity more effectively.&#10;&#10;References:&#10;1. Transcript excerpt provided in the question." />
    <node id="1. The session touched on the topic of weight management assistance for both adults and children, mentioning the need for a transformed primary care system that provides a range of healthcare professionals beyond just general practitioners (GPs). This transformation would include seeking more dietetic support in primary care settings to help address weight issues before they become significant problems.&#10;2. The concept of redesigning the pathway was discussed as a solution to making health services more accessible for those with weight management concerns, allowing them to easily find advice and support within their local healthcare system. This redesigned pathway would ideally connect patients with necessary services, preventing kids from developing weight issues and helping adults manage their existing conditions better.&#10;&#10;In summary, the session discussed the need for a transformed primary care system that offers diverse health professionals for better weight management support. Redesigning the healthcare pathway was proposed as a solution to help individuals access advice and support more easily within their local healthcare systems." />
    <node id="Speaker: Dr Frank Atherton&#10;Content: Well, it depends what you mean as to where to refer to. So, the health system obviously needs to respond to this issue. What we're seeing across the NHS is a gradual transformation in primary care so that primary care is no longer about going to see your GP, it's about going to see a practice where you have a range of health professionals. Would I like to see more dietetic support, for example, in that setting? Absolutely I would. I think we need to think in terms of that pathway that we were talking about earlier, about access to that kind of advice and support, which can head off people getting into problems and kids getting into problems with weight issues. So, that question of redesign of the pathway really speaks to, I think, your point about, 'Well, where do people go when they have problems with their weight?' That's true for adults and it's true for children as well.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. Are there any other questions from Members? No. Okay. Well, can I thank you both very much for your attendance? It's been a really productive session. We appreciate your time. You will be" />
    <node id=", so I know that only maybe 10 per cent, 15 per cent, possibly 20 per cent of what makes and keeps us healthy as individuals and as communities can be driven through the health system; but I would like the system to step up and take these kinds of issues more seriously as well. So I'd be looking for local leadership through directors of public health and indeed through chief executives to work with their public services boards on this. So, we'll need some sort of national oversight, absolutely, but we need local ownership and local leadership, too.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Thank you. We've got some questions now from Janet Finch-Saunders.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you, Chair. Delivery of the plan will be led by a national implementation board that will be accountable to Ministers. Which Minister do you believe it should be accountable to, or, given the complexity of obesity, should the board be directly accountable to the First Minister?&#10;Speaker: Dr Frank Atherton&#10;Content: Ultimately, the First Minister will be responsible for this and will want to have a strong oversight of this. It is often framed as a health issue, and the Minister, Vaughan Gething," />
    <node id="1. The draft plan proposes encouraging local leadership in promoting healthy habits in schools, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;2. The plan aims to address gaps in data on childhood obesity by implementing longitudinal measurements similar to England's approach, where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12.&#10;3. While not explicitly mentioned, providing sufficient support for very overweight children would likely involve Tier 3 interventions such as referrals to specialized healthcare services, family-based lifestyle weight management programs, or in some cases, medical treatment. The draft plan does not provide specifics on this matter.&#10;4. The Welsh government is open to additional suggestions for new proposals or improvements to existing programs such as Healthy Child Wales and breastfeeding support to address the influence of parents on children's healthy weight behaviors during the first 1,000 days.&#10;5. Increased investment will be required from the Welsh Government to support and fund initiatives aimed at tackling childhood obesity, focusing on evaluating the effectiveness of existing programs, improving their quality or extracting better value from them, and implementing new strategies based on best practices learned from other UK nations." />
    <node id="1. Increase affordability of healthy food: The Welsh Government could consider implementing policies that reduce the price difference between healthy and less healthy food options, making it easier for low-income families to access and choose nutritious meals. This may include subsidies or tax incentives for retailers to sell fresh produce at lower prices in deprived areas.&#10;&#10;2. Food education programs: Developing and funding educational initiatives that teach children and their parents about the importance of nutrition, cooking skills, and budgeting can help low-income families make healthier choices. These programs could be integrated into schools or offered through community centers.&#10;&#10;3. Strengthen food banks and similar organizations: Ensuring food banks provide healthy options by working with suppliers and setting guidelines for the types of food distributed can help low-income families access nutritious meals during challenging times. The Welsh Government could also consider increasing funding for food banks and similar organizations to enable them to better support those in need.&#10;&#10;4. Improve public transportation: By enhancing public transportation options, particularly in socioeconomically deprived areas, low-income families may find it easier to access grocery stores that offer fresh produce and other healthy food options at affordable prices.&#10;&#10;5. Urban planning and zoning regulations: Encouraging the development of supermarkets and grocery stores in underserved communities can improve access to healthy food for low-income families. This could involve revising zoning regulations or providing incentives for businesses to open locations in these areas.&#10;&#10;6. Incentivize retailers to offer healthier options: The Welsh Government could introduce policies that encourage retailers, particularly those operating in socioeconomically deprived communities, to stock and promote healthier food options. This may include tax breaks, subsidies, or other financial incentives for businesses that prioritize healthy eating.&#10;&#10;7. Monitor and regulate marketing practices: Implementing stricter regulations on the advertising and promotion of unhealthy food and beverages, especially in areas with high socioeconomic deprivation, can help protect low-income families from targeted marketing campaigns that contribute to poor dietary choices.&#10;&#10;8. Review and reform welfare policies: Ensuring that social security benefits and other welfare programs provide adequate support for low-income families to access and afford healthy food is crucial. This may involve increasing benefit levels, adjusting eligibility criteria, or introducing new programs specifically designed to address food insecurity among vulnerable populations.&#10;&#10;Estimating the exact investment required for these measures would depend on the specific policies and programs implemented; however, it is clear that additional funding will be necessary from the Welsh Government to support initiatives aimed at reducing socioeconomic disparities in overweight and obesity prevalence. This investment should focus on interventions with proven benefits and contribute to the overall goal of creating a society where all families have access to good-quality, affordable, and healthy food options." />
    <node id=" Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Finally, we know that for some families day-to-day challenges can make it difficult for them to make healthy choices, particularly for those on lower incomes and/or maybe using food banks. Could the Welsh Government take bolder action to better support low-income families to eat healthily?&#10;Speaker: Dr Frank Atherton&#10;Content: Well, you've touched on a really important point about inequalities because overweight and obesity is not evenly distributed across our population. It absolutely is more prevalent in more socioeconomically deprived communities, and that's something that should really concern us all. So, it gets you to questions of availability of fresh food and produce; it gets you to questions of formulation of products and whether value brands are less healthy than more premium brands. So, it cuts across all of those issues that we talked about in terms of settings and in terms of environment earlier. There is something about the affordability of good-quality healthy food that we need to think about. We do need to think in broad terms—broader terms than just obesity, but we do need to think in broad terms—about how we create a society where families have the wherewithal to lead healthy lives, and that gets" />
    <node id="1. The national implementation board responsible for delivering the obesity plan should be directly accountable to the First Minister of Wales, as stated by Dr. Frank Atherton in the transcript excerpt provided. This ensures strong oversight and alignment with broader government objectives related to childhood obesity reduction, given that obesity is often framed as a health issue." />
    <node id="1. Strengthening leadership and coordination in addressing childhood obesity: Establish a national implementation board directly accountable to the First Minister of Wales to oversee the delivery of the obesity plan, ensuring strong oversight and alignment with broader government objectives related to childhood obesity reduction.&#10;&#10;2. Encouraging local leadership in promoting healthy habits in schools: Support local school leaders in implementing policies that promote physical activity, nutritious food choices, and education on healthy lifestyles for students, staff, and parents.&#10;&#10;3. Implementing statutory guidance for physical education: Ensure proper focus and resources are dedicated to physical education in schools through the implementation of statutory guidance, helping children develop healthy habits from an early age.&#10;&#10;4. Engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies: Involve children and young people in informing anti-obesity strategies by conducting school visits, consultations, or other forums to gather their insights and suggestions on reducing childhood obesity.&#10;&#10;5. Developing targeted interventions for specific groups: Address the decline in physical activity among girls during teenage years through targeted interventions aimed at promoting physical activity and healthy lifestyles among this demographic.&#10;&#10;6. Forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales: Foster relationships between schools and public health organizations to drive population-level approaches to physical activity, nutrition, and overall well-being.&#10;&#10;7. Improving the quality of food provided at schools: Focus on enhancing the nutritional value and appeal of school meals, whether free or paid for, as well as addressing hunger at school through national-level initiatives.&#10;&#10;8. Examining potential benefits of additional measurements in the Child Measurement Programme: Implement a longitudinal measurement system similar to England's approach, where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12, to better understand the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children and improve data-driven decision-making for reducing childhood obesity.&#10;&#10;9. Evaluating existing programs and optimizing resources: Assess the effectiveness of existing child health investments, including those addressing obesity and overweight in children, to ensure that new resources are directed towards interventions with proven benefits and maximize their impact on reducing childhood obesity in Wales." />
