    <node id="Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Good morning, everyone. Welcome to the Children, Young People and Education Committee. We've received apologies for absence from Michelle Brown and Jack Sargeant; there are no substitutions. Can I ask if Members have any declarations of interest, please? No. Okay. We'll move on, then, to item 2, which is our scrutiny of the 'Healthy Weight: Healthy Wales' draft strategy, and I'm very pleased to welcome Dr Frank Atherton, the Chief Medical Officer for Wales, and Nathan Cook, who is the head of the healthy and active branch at Welsh Government. Thank you, both, for attending this morning. We're very much looking forward to hearing what you've got to say. If you're happy, we'll go straight into questions. If I can just start by asking about the fact that 'Healthy Weight: Healthy Wales' is an all-age strategy, really, and how confident you are that it will deliver for children and young people.&#10;Speaker: Dr Frank Atherton&#10;Content: Well, we're very confident. I mean, it has to, quite clearly. We do need to think about the present generation, the problems faced by the current" />
    <node id="1. The speakers discuss that while a figure of £8 million to £10 million has been mentioned as a potential investment for obesity reduction initiatives in Wales, no explicit assessment of how this money is being spent in other UK nations has been provided. However, they acknowledge the importance of understanding the effectiveness of existing programs and seeking ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources.&#10;   &#10;2. It is essential to analyze the strategies implemented in other UK nations to address childhood obesity and determine if similar approaches can be adapted in Wales. By learning from successful initiatives in these regions, Welsh policymakers can make more informed decisions about how to effectively allocate resources for their own obesity reduction plan. This would require researching and evaluating the outcomes of existing programs in other UK nations and understanding the key elements that contribute to their success.&#10;&#10;Answer: There has not been an explicit mention of any assessments made of how the potential £10 million investment is being spent in other UK nations to address obesity. However, speakers recognize the importance of understanding the effectiveness of existing programs and seeking ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources. To make more informed decisions about resource allocation for a Welsh obesity reduction plan, it would be beneficial to research and evaluate the outcomes of successful initiatives in other UK nations and understand the key elements that contribute to their success." />
    <node id="1. Yes, the Welsh Government should still use the funding from the soft drink levy to fund public health programs targeted at addressing obesity, even if the revenue is less than anticipated due to successful reformulation by the industry. Dr. Frank Atherton, Chief Medical Officer for Wales, mentioned that there are consequentials coming to the Welsh Government as part of this levy, and although it is less than expected, the funding should be utilized for public health initiatives. However, Dr. Atherton expressed his disfavor for hypothecation (designating funds for specific uses) and emphasized considering the totality of resources going into public health programs rather than focusing on marginal amounts of money from specific sources.&#10;&#10;Using the revenue from the soft drink levy to fund obesity reduction initiatives would align with the goal of improving child health in Wales, including addressing obesity and overweight issues in children. While there is currently no explicit mention of setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student, the focus is on encouraging local leadership, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;&#10;Although increased investment will be required from the Welsh Government to support and fund initiatives aimed at tackling childhood obesity, it is crucial to assess the effectiveness of existing programs and seek ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources. This approach will help ensure that investments are directed towards interventions with proven benefits and contribute to the overall goal of reducing childhood obesity in Wales." />
    <node id="1. The strategy development board is currently open to considering the idea of setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student to support health and education objectives in schools, but it has not been explicitly included in their plans so far. This could be addressed in the consultation response if raised specifically.&#10;2. To improve the implementation of standards for healthy preschools, Dr. Frank Atherton suggests tightening existing standards and enforcing them more strictly to ensure compliance. He believes that local school leaders should be responsible for ensuring compliance with physical activity guidelines in preschools under the new curriculum, which places obligations on them regarding what they do in their schools to promote healthy weight and well-being in children." />
    <node id="Yes, the Welsh Government should allocate the funding from the soft drink levy towards obesity prevention programs from the general revenue pool. This approach aligns with Dr. Frank Atherton's preference against hypothecation and his focus on the totality of resources going into public health programs rather than specific sources.&#10;&#10;The success of the levy in reducing sugar content has resulted in a smaller than anticipated revenue of £56 million over two years. However, this reduction in revenue indicates a positive outcome – the reformulation by the industry and decrease in sugar content in soft drinks.&#10;&#10;Instead of earmarking the funding for specific public health uses, it is more beneficial to allocate it from the general revenue pool. This allows for a more comprehensive approach to addressing obesity prevention, as the government can divert and channel some of the £7 billion spent on health and social care towards broad prevention initiatives, including tackling being overweight and obesity in particular.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, although the revenue from the soft drink levy is smaller than anticipated, it should still be used to fund obesity prevention programs, given Dr. Frank Atherton's stance on hypothecation and the importance of considering the totality of resources going into public health programs." />
