    <edge source="1. Address the root causes of health issues: Dr Frank Atherton mentioned that making every contact count is important, but there are difficulties in availability of people to refer to. To improve this situation, we need to think broadly about how to create a society where families have the means to lead healthy lives, which involves addressing deeper determinants of health such as the minimum wage and income poverty.&#10;&#10;2. Implement strong evaluation: Whoever is responsible for producing the final strategy needs to ensure that it includes strong evaluation with appropriate metrics, whether they are framed as targets or ambitions. This will help determine the effectiveness of various programs and identify areas where improvements can be made.&#10;&#10;3. Increase investment and assess current spending: The Welsh Government should invest in actions aimed at reducing childhood obesity and support those actions effectively. An assessment of the level of investment needed to implement this plan should be carried out, keeping in mind that the effectiveness of existing programs needs to be evaluated before determining new investments. It is essential to look at existing programs, determine their effectiveness, and seek ways to improve them or extract better value from them.&#10;&#10;4. Collaborate with other UK nations: Lynne Neagle AM suggested looking into how money is being spent in other UK nations to directly impact obesity. This could provide valuable insights on best practices and strategies that have proven effective in addressing the issue. By learning from these experiences, Wales can improve its own approach to making every contact count and increase availability of appropriate referrals within the healthcare system." target="The level of investment needed to effectively implement a plan for reducing childhood obesity cannot be quantified precisely without knowing the exact details of the actions to be taken. However, it is clear that increased investment will be required from the Welsh Government to support and fund initiatives aimed at tackling childhood obesity. This investment should focus on evaluating the effectiveness of existing programs, improving their quality or extracting better value from them, and implementing new strategies based on best practices learned from other UK nations.&#10;&#10;Currently, the Welsh Government does make investments in areas related to child health, including those that address obesity and overweight in children. To determine the appropriate level of investment for a childhood obesity reduction plan, it is essential to assess the effectiveness of these existing programs and seek ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources. This approach will help ensure that investments are directed towards interventions with proven benefits and contribute to the overall goal of reducing childhood obesity in Wales.">
