ledged that setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student to support health and education objectives in schools is not explicitly mentioned in the transcript. However, there are discussions on encouraging local leadership, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;4. Addressing gaps in data on childhood obesity is considered essential, and implementing longitudinal measurements similar to England's approach (where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12) could provide valuable information on the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children. This information would help direct initiatives to reduce childhood obesity more effectively.&#10;&#10;References:&#10;1. Transcript excerpt provided in the question.">
