    <edge source="1. Regarding staffing numbers in schools, do you believe that there should be a specific target or range set for the number of staff members per student to support the health and education objectives of the plan?&#10;2. For improving the implementation of standards for healthy preschools, would you consider it appropriate to enforce those standards more strictly, and if so, what measures could be taken to ensure compliance?" target="1. Potential Benefits of Universal School Meals:&#10;&#09;* Ensures that all children have access to good-quality food at school (Janet Finch-Saunders AM).&#10;&#09;* Levels the playing field by providing equal and nutritious meal options for all students, regardless of their socioeconomic background (Janet Finch-Saunders AM).&#10;&#09;* Can potentially improve children's overall diet and health outcomes (Dr Frank Atherton).&#10;2. Challenges of Universal School Meals:&#10;&#09;* Difficulty in policing the quality of packed lunches, as it could infringe on parental autonomy (Janet Finch-Saunders AM).&#10;&#09;* Financial implications and potential resistance from parents who prefer providing their children with packed lunches (Dr Frank Atherton).&#10;3. Addressing Quality of Packed Lunches:&#10;&#09;* Encourage awareness and education among parents about the importance of nutritious food in packed lunches.&#10;&#09;* Offer resources and support for parents to make healthier choices, without implementing strict regulations on packed lunch contents (Janet Finch-Saunders AM).&#10;4. Role of Parental Policing:&#10;&#09;* A balance should be struck between encouraging healthy choices and respecting parental autonomy over their children's meals (Janet Finch-Saunders AM).&#10;&#09;* Encouraging partnerships between schools, Public Health Wales, and local communities to drive population-level approaches to promoting healthier food choices in packed lunches (Dr Frank Atherton).">
