    <edge source="1. Regarding staffing numbers in schools, do you believe that there should be a specific target or range set for the number of staff members per student to support the health and education objectives of the plan?&#10;2. For improving the implementation of standards for healthy preschools, would you consider it appropriate to enforce those standards more strictly, and if so, what measures could be taken to ensure compliance?" target="1. There is currently no explicit mention of setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student to support health and education objectives in schools. The focus is on encouraging local leadership, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;&#10;2. Yes, addressing gaps in data on childhood obesity could be improved by implementing longitudinal measurements similar to England's approach, where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12. This would provide valuable information on the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children and help direct initiatives to reduce childhood obesity more effectively.&#10;&#10;Reference(s):&#10;1. Transcript excerpt provided in the question.">
