    <edge source=" phase. And while you're quite right—obviously, parents have a role in this, or families—there will be, particularly with the introduction of the new curriculum, certain expectations on schools to provide not just healthy environments but to actively work towards well-being and healthy weight in children and things. And that's why I asked you about local leadership, because, if it fails for reasons that have nothing to do with the plan at foundation phase, it's going to fail further up the school years as well. I think it might be something that the board might want to consider here, because at some point there'll be an accountability question and we will want to know how 'Healthy Weight: Healthy Wales' fits in with the new plans for the new curriculum, and whether it's merely persuasive and influential or whether it has the weight to place some obligations on school leaders about what they do in their schools. So, this connection, I think, is quite an important one, and, if the strategy development board could consider that, I think it would be very helpful, because this doesn't exist in a vacuum.&#10;Speaker: Dr Frank Atherton&#10;Content: Well, I'd certainly be delighted to take that back and we can look at it" target="1. Establish clear leadership: Dr Frank Atherton mentioned the importance of leadership and the need for a structure to lead the implementation of the healthy weight strategy. While he is not in favor of creating new structures, he believes that leadership should come from the top down with political commitment. He also acknowledges the need for public sector engagement, as well as collaboration with industry, communities, and the public.&#10;&#10;2. Governance systems alignment: Dr Atherton discussed the importance of aligning governance systems, such as Public Services Boards and Regional Partnership Boards, to drive this common agenda forward, ensuring that the healthy weight strategy is not considered in isolation but as part of a broader prevention strategy.&#10;&#10;3. School accountability: Sian Gwenllian AM suggested that the strategy development board consider connecting the 'Healthy Weight: Healthy Wales' strategy with the new curriculum, making school leaders responsible for implementing healthy weight initiatives in their schools. Dr Frank Atherton agreed to take this suggestion back for further discussion.&#10;&#10;4. Regular evaluation and metrics: Dr Atherton emphasized the importance of having a strong evaluation component in the final strategy, including metrics to measure progress. These metrics could be framed as targets or ambitions, depending on the outcome of consultations.&#10;&#10;5. Engaging children and young people: The plan includes measures to engage children and young people in informing anti-obesity strategies through various forums, such as school visits and consultations. This involvement can help ensure that the strategy is relevant and effective for the target audience.&#10;&#10;6. Partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales: Exploring opportunities for partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales can help drive population-level approaches to physical activity, ensuring a consistent and coordinated effort across relevant partners.">
