    <edge source="1. Encourage local leadership in promoting healthy habits in schools, including physical activity in early primary education.&#10;2. Consider the implementation of statutory guidance for schools on physical education to ensure proper focus and resources.&#10;3. Engage with children and young people to inform anti-obesity strategies through various forums, such as school visits and consultations.&#10;4. Develop targeted interventions to address the decline in physical activity among girls during teenage years.&#10;5. Explore opportunities for partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales to drive population-level approaches to physical activity.&#10;6. Focus on improving the quality of food provided at schools, whether it is free or paid for, as well as addressing hunger at school through national-level initiatives.&#10;7. Examine the potential benefits of having a second measurement taking place in the Child Measurement Programme to better understand the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children." target="1. Strengthening leadership and coordination in addressing childhood obesity: Establish a national implementation board directly accountable to the First Minister of Wales to oversee the delivery of the obesity plan, ensuring strong oversight and alignment with broader government objectives related to childhood obesity reduction.&#10;&#10;2. Encouraging local leadership in promoting healthy habits in schools: Support local school leaders in implementing policies that promote physical activity, nutritious food choices, and education on healthy lifestyles for students, staff, and parents.&#10;&#10;3. Implementing statutory guidance for physical education: Ensure proper focus and resources are dedicated to physical education in schools through the implementation of statutory guidance, helping children develop healthy habits from an early age.&#10;&#10;4. Engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies: Involve children and young people in informing anti-obesity strategies by conducting school visits, consultations, or other forums to gather their insights and suggestions on reducing childhood obesity.&#10;&#10;5. Developing targeted interventions for specific groups: Address the decline in physical activity among girls during teenage years through targeted interventions aimed at promoting physical activity and healthy lifestyles among this demographic.&#10;&#10;6. Forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales: Foster relationships between schools and public health organizations to drive population-level approaches to physical activity, nutrition, and overall well-being.&#10;&#10;7. Improving the quality of food provided at schools: Focus on enhancing the nutritional value and appeal of school meals, whether free or paid for, as well as addressing hunger at school through national-level initiatives.&#10;&#10;8. Examining potential benefits of additional measurements in the Child Measurement Programme: Implement a longitudinal measurement system similar to England's approach, where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12, to better understand the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children and improve data-driven decision-making for reducing childhood obesity.&#10;&#10;9. Evaluating existing programs and optimizing resources: Assess the effectiveness of existing child health investments, including those addressing obesity and overweight in children, to ensure that new resources are directed towards interventions with proven benefits and maximize their impact on reducing childhood obesity in Wales.">
