    <edge source=" Can I just ask about the child measurement programme? The strategy commits to looking at whether we can have a second measurement taking place in Wales. Can you just tell us a bit more about your thinking on that and when you would see a second measurement taking place and how you would use that data?&#10;Speaker: Dr Frank Atherton&#10;Content: I touched on that just now, but personally I do think it would be helpful to have more information. It's always the case, There's always a trade-off between the cost of getting that information and the value of the information. So, the question of how it would be used would be really important. There is still a lot that we don't know. We know an awful lot about obesity and being overweight and the causes of it, but we don't really have a very clear understanding, in Wales at least, of the point at which children start to become overweight. Although we know that overweight children tend to go on to become overweight adults, we don't know what proportion of them between school entry and later teenage years—what those changes are. So, it would help us to have some better understanding, which would help to direct some of our initiatives. I'd be generally supportive of the principle. We" target="1. There is currently no explicit mention of setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student to support health and education objectives in schools. The focus is on encouraging local leadership, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;&#10;2. While the transcript does not explicitly mention enforcing healthy preschool standards more strictly, there is discussion about addressing gaps in data on childhood obesity and considering a longitudinal measurement system similar to England's, where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12. This would provide valuable information on the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children and help direct initiatives to reduce childhood obesity.">
