    <edge source="1. Implementing a commitment to embed physical activity at an early stage in primary school education would involve creating an environment that encourages and promotes regular movement and exercise throughout the day. This could include:&#10;* Integrating physical activity into daily classroom routines, such as active lessons or brain breaks&#10;* Providing adequate space and equipment for physical education classes and recess&#10;* Training teachers to incorporate movement into their teaching methods&#10;* Encouraging parental involvement in promoting physical activity outside of school hours. &#10;2. Increasing the number of children who meet the recommended physical activity guidelines can be achieved by creating a positive and supportive environment that makes physical activity fun, accessible, and part of the daily routine. Research shows that children who are more physically active tend to have better academic performance, improved mental health, and reduced risk of chronic diseases. By prioritizing physical activity in primary education, schools can play a critical role in shaping healthy habits that last a lifetime." target="1. Health impact assessments (HIAs) can be utilized more extensively by applying them to a broader range of policy decisions and public infrastructure developments, such as those related to the public sector. This approach would ensure that health considerations are incorporated into various aspects of policymaking and development processes.&#10;2. For schools specifically, HIAs could help create healthier environments for students and the wider community. Given that schools are not just for children but also serve as community resources, using sports facilities in schools similar to how leisure centers are used can be a good principle to pursue. This would involve breaking down barriers to make these facilities more accessible to the public.&#10;3. Local leadership should promote healthy habits in schools, including physical activity during early primary education. Statutory guidance for schools on physical education could ensure proper focus and resources. Engaging with children and young people to inform anti-obesity strategies is also crucial. Developing targeted interventions for specific groups, such as teenage girls, can help address the decline in physical activity among them.&#10;4. Partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales could drive population-level approaches to physical activity. Improving the quality of food provided at schools and addressing hunger through national-level initiatives are also essential components of promoting healthier school environments.&#10;5. A second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme can provide a better understanding of the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children, informing future strategies and interventions.">
