    <edge source="1. Implementing a commitment to embed physical activity at an early stage in primary school education would involve creating an environment that encourages and promotes regular movement and exercise throughout the day. This could include:&#10;* Integrating physical activity into daily classroom routines, such as active lessons or brain breaks&#10;* Providing adequate space and equipment for physical education classes and recess&#10;* Training teachers to incorporate movement into their teaching methods&#10;* Encouraging parental involvement in promoting physical activity outside of school hours. &#10;2. Increasing the number of children who meet the recommended physical activity guidelines can be achieved by creating a positive and supportive environment that makes physical activity fun, accessible, and part of the daily routine. Research shows that children who are more physically active tend to have better academic performance, improved mental health, and reduced risk of chronic diseases. By prioritizing physical activity in primary education, schools can play a critical role in shaping healthy habits that last a lifetime." target="The level of investment needed to effectively implement a plan for reducing childhood obesity cannot be quantified precisely without knowing the exact details of the actions to be taken. However, it is clear that increased investment will be required from the Welsh Government to support and fund initiatives aimed at tackling childhood obesity. This investment should focus on evaluating the effectiveness of existing programs, improving their quality or extracting better value from them, and implementing new strategies based on best practices learned from other UK nations.&#10;&#10;Currently, the Welsh Government does make investments in areas related to child health, including those that address obesity and overweight in children. To determine the appropriate level of investment for a childhood obesity reduction plan, it is essential to assess the effectiveness of these existing programs and seek ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources. This approach will help ensure that investments are directed towards interventions with proven benefits and contribute to the overall goal of reducing childhood obesity in Wales.">
