    <edge source="The level of investment needed to effectively implement a plan for reducing childhood obesity cannot be quantified precisely without knowing the exact details of the actions to be taken. However, it is clear that increased investment will be required from the Welsh Government to support and fund initiatives aimed at tackling childhood obesity. This investment should focus on evaluating the effectiveness of existing programs, improving their quality or extracting better value from them, and implementing new strategies based on best practices learned from other UK nations.&#10;&#10;Currently, the Welsh Government does make investments in areas related to child health, including those that address obesity and overweight in children. To determine the appropriate level of investment for a childhood obesity reduction plan, it is essential to assess the effectiveness of these existing programs and seek ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources. This approach will help ensure that investments are directed towards interventions with proven benefits and contribute to the overall goal of reducing childhood obesity in Wales." target="1. Yes, the Welsh Government should still use the funding from the soft drink levy to fund public health programs targeted at addressing obesity, even if the revenue is less than anticipated due to successful reformulation by the industry. Dr. Frank Atherton, Chief Medical Officer for Wales, mentioned that there are consequentials coming to the Welsh Government as part of this levy, and although it is less than expected, the funding should be utilized for public health initiatives. However, Dr. Atherton expressed his disfavor for hypothecation (designating funds for specific uses) and emphasized considering the totality of resources going into public health programs rather than focusing on marginal amounts of money from specific sources.&#10;&#10;Using the revenue from the soft drink levy to fund obesity reduction initiatives would align with the goal of improving child health in Wales, including addressing obesity and overweight issues in children. While there is currently no explicit mention of setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student, the focus is on encouraging local leadership, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;&#10;Although increased investment will be required from the Welsh Government to support and fund initiatives aimed at tackling childhood obesity, it is crucial to assess the effectiveness of existing programs and seek ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources. This approach will help ensure that investments are directed towards interventions with proven benefits and contribute to the overall goal of reducing childhood obesity in Wales.">
