    <edge source="1. To address the issue of children not meeting physical activity guidelines, Sport Wales, Public Health Wales, and Natural Resources Wales are currently working together as a collaborative to enhance the joint delivery of physical activity programs for children. They are specifically focusing on improving the efficiency of existing school programs, such as eco-schools, the Welsh network of healthy schools, and sports programs. The goal is to create better alignment and coordination among these initiatives to encourage increased physical activity among children in school settings.&#10;2. Increasing the number of physically active children can have numerous positive impacts on their lives, including better academic performance, improved mental health, and reduced risk of chronic diseases. To achieve this goal, it is essential to create a supportive environment that integrates physical activity into daily routines, makes it fun and accessible, and involves parents and teachers in promoting healthy habits. By prioritizing physical activity in primary education, schools can contribute significantly to shaping lifelong healthy behaviors among children." target="1. Tailor physical activities to different audiences and interests, as not all children enjoy organized team sports. This can include individual activities and diverse options that cater to various preferences.&#10;2. Collaborate between Sport Wales, Public Health Wales, and other organizations to create a population approach in driving physical activity, ensuring it's enjoyable and attractive to people of all ages and genders.&#10;3. Develop targeted interventions to address the decline in physical activity among girls during teenage years, taking into account their specific needs, interests, and preferences.&#10;4. Encourage local leadership in promoting healthy habits in schools, including physical activity during early primary education for both boys and girls. Statutory guidance for schools on physical education can help ensure proper focus and resources.&#10;5. Integrate physical activity into daily classroom routines, such as active lessons or brain breaks, to create an environment that encourages and promotes regular movement and exercise throughout the day.&#10;6. Train teachers to incorporate movement into their teaching methods and provide adequate space and equipment for physical education classes and recess, making it fun, accessible, and part of the daily routine for all students.">
