ort for parents to make informed decisions about their children's meals.&#10;&#10;4. Consider a universal school meal program: Implementing a universal school meal program can ensure that all children have access to good-quality food at school, leveling the playing field and providing equal and nutritious meal options for all students regardless of their socioeconomic background. This approach can potentially improve children's overall diet and health outcomes.&#10;&#10;5. Update healthy eating regulations: As mentioned during the discussion, updating the 2013 healthy eating in schools regulations to adhere to current Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition guidelines around sugar levels can help reduce the amount of sugar consumed by students during school hours. This could involve setting maximum sugar content limits for food and beverages provided or sold at schools.">
