    <edge source="1. Area of Education Policy Open to Consideration: Dr. Frank Atherton is open to considering the idea of setting a specific target or range for the number of staff members per student to support the health and education objectives of the plan, as he acknowledges that it is not his area of expertise and hasn't been discussed in the development of the strategy. He agrees to consider this point if it is specifically raised in the consultation response from the committee.&#10;2. Improving Implementation of Standards for Healthy Preschools: Dr. Frank Atherton suggests improving the implementation of standards for healthy preschools by potentially tightening the existing standards and enforcing them more strictly, ensuring compliance through proper implementation. He also mentions that there will be expectations on schools to provide not just healthy environments but to actively work towards well-being and healthy weight in children under the new curriculum. Dr. Atherton emphasizes the importance of local leadership to ensure accountability and the successful integration of 'Healthy Weight: Healthy Wales' with the new curriculum plans, which will place obligations on school leaders about what they do in their schools." target=" vacuum.&#10;Speaker: Dr Frank Atherton&#10;Content: Well, I'd certainly be delighted to take that back and we can look at it in terms of how we move from the consultation into the final strategy. It's certainly a point we can try and look at.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Because we will want to know who to ask: 'you're the accountable person—why has something worked, or not worked?' We will need to know that at some point.&#10;Speaker: Dr Frank Atherton&#10;Content: Just building on Nathan's point, some of the schools—I know it's schools rather than the preschools, and I take your point, but some of the schools we've been working with have absolutely brilliant models of good practice and good local leadership. I remember the Minister actually at the launch, and one of the schools was represented there, and they presented—the school came and some of the children came and presented—to the whole audience about the activities that they were undertaking in their school around physical activity and on healthy eating, and it was such a model of good behaviour the question was, 'Well, why not everywhere?', so that probably speaks to your question.&#10;Speaker">
