    <edge source="1. There is currently no explicit mention of setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student to support health and education objectives in schools. The focus is on encouraging local leadership, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;&#10;2. While the transcript does not explicitly mention enforcing healthy preschool standards more strictly, there is discussion about addressing gaps in data on childhood obesity and considering a longitudinal measurement system similar to England's, where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12. This would provide valuable information on the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children and help direct initiatives to reduce childhood obesity." target=" 11—at age 11 or 12., that kind of age group. And so you do have a longitudinal view over time of what's happening to children. I think that would be helpful to us in Wales, and it's one of the questions in the consultation about whether we should expand that. Obviously, that would have significant resource implications, not just for the funding, but also for schools and for the system to deliver it. But it's something that maybe would help us in terms of better understanding and better evaluation—the point that was made earlier.&#10;Speaker: Nathan Cook&#10;Content: And the other data we do have is the millennium cohort study, which has been released, for 14 and 15-year-olds. That's going to be—. We're starting to think about how we can utilise some of that data, looking at that longitudinal picture around children as well, which will be really helpful.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you. You've answered my next question. Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Can I just ask about the child measurement programme? The strategy commits to looking at whether we can have a second measurement taking place in Wales. Can you just tell">
