y strategies: Involve children and young people in informing anti-obesity strategies by conducting school visits, consultations, or other forums to gather their insights and suggestions on reducing childhood obesity.&#10;&#10;5. Developing targeted interventions for specific groups: Address the decline in physical activity among girls during teenage years through targeted interventions aimed at promoting physical activity and healthy lifestyles among this demographic.&#10;&#10;6. Forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales: Foster relationships between schools and public health organizations to drive population-level approaches to physical activity, nutrition, and overall well-being.&#10;&#10;7. Improving the quality of food provided at schools: Focus on enhancing the nutritional value and appeal of school meals, whether free or paid for, as well as addressing hunger at school through national-level initiatives.&#10;&#10;8. Examining potential benefits of additional measurements in the Child Measurement Programme: Implement a longitudinal measurement system similar to England's approach, where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12, to better understand the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children and improve data-driven decision-making for reducing childhood obesity.&#10;&#10;9. Evaluating existing programs and optimizing resources: Assess the effectiveness of existing child health investments, including those addressing obesity and overweight in children, to ensure that new resources are directed towards interventions with proven benefits and maximize their impact on reducing childhood obesity in Wales.">
