    <edge source="1. There is currently no explicit mention of setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student to support health and education objectives in schools. The focus is on encouraging local leadership, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;&#10;2. Yes, addressing gaps in data on childhood obesity could be improved by implementing longitudinal measurements similar to England's approach, where children are measured at school entry and again at age 11 or 12. This would provide valuable information on the development of overweight and obesity in Welsh children and help direct initiatives to reduce childhood obesity more effectively.&#10;&#10;Reference(s):&#10;1. Transcript excerpt provided in the question." target="1. The speakers discuss that while a figure of £8 million to £10 million has been mentioned as a potential investment for obesity reduction initiatives in Wales, no explicit assessment of how this money is being spent in other UK nations has been provided. However, they acknowledge the importance of understanding the effectiveness of existing programs and seeking ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources.&#10;   &#10;2. It is essential to analyze the strategies implemented in other UK nations to address childhood obesity and determine if similar approaches can be adapted in Wales. By learning from successful initiatives in these regions, Welsh policymakers can make more informed decisions about how to effectively allocate resources for their own obesity reduction plan. This would require researching and evaluating the outcomes of existing programs in other UK nations and understanding the key elements that contribute to their success.&#10;&#10;Answer: There has not been an explicit mention of any assessments made of how the potential £10 million investment is being spent in other UK nations to address obesity. However, speakers recognize the importance of understanding the effectiveness of existing programs and seeking ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources. To make more informed decisions about resource allocation for a Welsh obesity reduction plan, it would be beneficial to research and evaluate the outcomes of successful initiatives in other UK nations and understand the key elements that contribute to their success.">
