    <edge source="1. Yes, the Welsh Government should still use the funding from the soft drink levy to fund public health programs targeted at addressing obesity, even if the revenue is less than anticipated due to successful reformulation by the industry. Dr. Frank Atherton, Chief Medical Officer for Wales, mentioned that there are consequentials coming to the Welsh Government as part of this levy, and although it is less than expected, the funding should be utilized for public health initiatives. However, Dr. Atherton expressed his disfavor for hypothecation (designating funds for specific uses) and emphasized considering the totality of resources going into public health programs rather than focusing on marginal amounts of money from specific sources.&#10;&#10;Using the revenue from the soft drink levy to fund obesity reduction initiatives would align with the goal of improving child health in Wales, including addressing obesity and overweight issues in children. While there is currently no explicit mention of setting specific targets or ranges for staff members per student, the focus is on encouraging local leadership, implementing statutory guidance for physical education, engaging children and young people in anti-obesity strategies, developing targeted interventions for girls, forming partnerships between schools and Public Health Wales, improving the quality of school food, and examining the potential benefits of a second measurement in the Child Measurement Programme.&#10;&#10;Although increased investment will be required from the Welsh Government to support and fund initiatives aimed at tackling childhood obesity, it is crucial to assess the effectiveness of existing programs and seek ways to improve or optimize their impact before committing new resources. This approach will help ensure that investments are directed towards interventions with proven benefits and contribute to the overall goal of reducing childhood obesity in Wales." target="Yes, the Welsh Government should allocate the funding from the soft drink levy towards obesity prevention programs from the general revenue pool. This approach aligns with Dr. Frank Atherton's preference against hypothecation and his focus on the totality of resources going into public health programs rather than specific sources.&#10;&#10;The success of the levy in reducing sugar content has resulted in a smaller than anticipated revenue of £56 million over two years. However, this reduction in revenue indicates a positive outcome – the reformulation by the industry and decrease in sugar content in soft drinks.&#10;&#10;Instead of earmarking the funding for specific public health uses, it is more beneficial to allocate it from the general revenue pool. This allows for a more comprehensive approach to addressing obesity prevention, as the government can divert and channel some of the £7 billion spent on health and social care towards broad prevention initiatives, including tackling being overweight and obesity in particular.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, although the revenue from the soft drink levy is smaller than anticipated, it should still be used to fund obesity prevention programs, given Dr. Frank Atherton's stance on hypothecation and the importance of considering the totality of resources going into public health programs.">
